article.headline: Oral Roberts 87, Tulsa 81
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- For Oral Roberts' players Josh Atkinson, Caleb Green and Ralph Charles, Saturday's victory over crosstown rival Tulsa was more than just the team's fourth win of the season. The native Tulsans combined for 62 points as the Golden Eagles beat the Golden Hurricane 87-81. "It meant a lot to all of us," said Atkinson, a 6-foot-3 senior guard. "Me, Caleb, Ralph and (center) Matt Gastel, we all know what this game means. We were ready to play." Atkinson produced 25 points and four assists, while Green, a 6-7 freshman forward, had 24 points and 13 rebounds. Each scored 14 in the second half for the Golden Eagles (4-3), who defeated the Golden Hurricane (2-3) for the first time in their annual meeting since 1999. Charles scored seven of his 13 points in the final 2:46 for ORU while Jonathan Bluitt chipped in 14 points and six assists. Jarius Glenn led all scorers with 26 points and eight rebounds for Tulsa (2-3). Jason Parker added 23 points while Charles Ramsdell posted 13 points and eight rebounds. Glenn scored 17 points in the first half to help Tulsa rally from an 11-point deficit for a 44-43 lead at intermission. "We got off to a horrendous start," Tulsa coach John Phillips said. "ORU couldn't miss, but I was proud of our guys the way they fought back. "ORU did a great job down the stretch of getting the ball to the right people. Our game plan was to get the ball inside and we just didn't do it in the second half. We're a basketball team trying to figure out who we are and how we need to play." In the second half, the lead seesawed until Atkinson's basket put ORU ahead 57-56 with 12:32 left. Green scored five straight points to give ORU a 72-66 lead at 5:59. Tulsa cut its deficit to one before Charles' layup boosted the Golden Eagles' lead to 83-80 with 1:13 remaining. Parker missed a 3-pointer on Tulsa's next possession and Charles rebounded. After Bluitt misfired on a trey, Green grabbed the offensive rebound that led to Ken Tutt's two free throws with 21 seconds left. Charles added two free throws with nine seconds left to clinch the win for ORU. "Our two seniors, Josh and Ralph, were terrific," ORU coach Scott Sutton said. "They knew how important this game was and how important it was to our program." ORU's win was only its fourth in its last 28 games against Tulsa. the Golden Eagles scored the game's first nine points and built their lead to 28-17 before TU responded with a 9-0 run. Glenn's 3-point play gave Tulsa a 38-37 lead with 4:38 left. After Gastel's dunk snapped a 41-41 tie at 1:02, Parker made a 3-pointer with 24 seconds left to give Tulsa a 44-43 lead at intermission.
